          "title": "Recommission, not retirement — and faithful succession",
          "body": "YHWH's answer to Elijah's death-prayer (19:4) is not death but assignment (19:15-16). Three anointings: Hazael (foreign king as instrument of judgment), Jehu (covenant-faithful purge of Ahab's house), and Elisha (prophetic successor). Elijah will actually perform only the third in person; the others he transmits forward (Elisha anoints Jehu through a son of the prophets in 2 Kings 9:1-10; Hazael's accession comes through Elisha's word in 2 Kings 8:7-15). The pattern matters: YHWH distributes His judgment across instruments and generations. The prophet is not the lone executor of divine purpose, and the *I alone am left* perception is geometrically wrong — Elisha, the 7,000, the future kings, and the succeeding prophetic line are all already present in YHWH's calendar. The chapter closes with Elisha burning his plow and slaughtering his oxen (19:21), an irreversible public act of joining the prophetic mission. The man who thought he was the last becomes the first of a chain that will run through Elisha, Jonah, Amos, Hosea, and ultimately John the Baptist (Matthew 17:10-13)."
