        "title": "Elisha at the plow — succession as the answer to isolation",
        "range": "19:19-21",
        "excerpt": "So he departed from there and found Elisha the son of Shaphat, while he was plowing with twelve pairs of oxen before him, and he with the twelfth. And Elijah passed over to him and threw his mantle on him.",
        "body": "Elijah obeys. He departs Horeb, retraces his way north, and finds Elisha *plowing with twelve yoke of oxen before him, and he with the twelfth* (19:19). The detail is loaded. Twelve yoke (twenty-four oxen total) signals substantial wealth — a small landowner with serious agricultural capital, plowing a major field with eleven workers and himself on the last team. The number twelve is also irresistibly tribal — one yoke per tribe of Israel. The narrator places the successor of the man who said *I alone am left* in a frame that visually represents the whole covenant people. Elijah has been answering his own *I alone* lament without realizing it: the moment he reaches Abel-meholah, he is met by a man whose work formation has twelve teams.\n\nThe call itself is wordless. Elijah passes by and throws his *adderet* (mantle) on Elisha. No speech, no commission, no instruction. The mantle is the same cloak Elijah wrapped his face in at Horeb (19:13) — the symbol of prophetic office, identified with the prophet's person. Throwing it on Elisha transfers the office without paperwork. Elisha understands. The narrative assumes prophetic vocation is recognized when it is given. The wordless call is reminiscent of Jesus' *follow Me* to Matthew at the tax booth (Matthew 9:9) and the fishermen at the lake (Matthew 4:18-22) — prophetic call does not require negotiation.\n\nElisha *leaves the oxen and runs after Elijah* (19:20), then asks: *let me kiss my father and my mother, then I will follow you.* The request is filial, not evasive — he wants to honor his parents in the departure, not delay it. Elijah's response is opaque in Hebrew: *lekh shuv, ki meh asiti lekha* — literally *go, return; for what have I done to you?* The phrase is variously read. Some take it as permission with a gentle reminder: *go and return; remember what I just did to you (with the mantle).* Others as testing irony: *go back if you wish; what did I do to you anyway?* Either way, the response leaves the initiative with Elisha. The call has been issued; the response must be free.\n\nElisha's response is decisive and irreversible (19:21). He takes the *pair of oxen* (his own team, the twelfth that he was driving), *sacrifices them, and boils their flesh with the implements (keli) of the oxen* — that is, he uses the wooden plow and yoke as fuel for the fire. He burns the means of his livelihood to cook the animals of his livelihood and feeds *the people* (whose people? — probably his farming community, possibly his family and workers). The act is publicly visible and economically permanent. There is no plow to return to. The oxen are dead, the equipment burned, the meat distributed. He has eaten his bridges.\n\nThen *he arose and followed Elijah and ministered to him* (*wayesharetehu*, v. 21). The verb *sharat* is the priestly-service word — used of Aaron's ministry (Exodus 28:35), Samuel's ministry to Eli (1 Samuel 2:11; 3:1), and Joshua's ministry to Moses (Exodus 24:13; Joshua 1:1). Elisha does not begin as Elijah's equal; he begins as his servant. The man who would pour water on Elijah's hands (2 Kings 3:11) starts here. Prophetic succession runs through apprenticeship.\n\nFor Elijah, the answer to *I alone am left* is now complete and personal. The 7,000 he could not see are out in the kingdom. The two future kings (Hazael, Jehu) are on the way. And the prophetic successor is now walking beside him, carrying his water and learning his rhythm. The chapter that opened with one terrified man running for his nephesh closes with two men walking together on the road back into the kingdom. The geography has reversed. The isolation has reversed. The death-prayer has been answered with company.\n\nA final canonical note. When Jesus is asked by a would-be disciple, *Permit me first to go and say goodbye to those at home* (Luke 9:61), He answers, *No one, after putting his hand to the plow and looking back, is fit for the kingdom of God* (Luke 9:62). The image is drawn directly from 1 Kings 19:19-21. But where Elijah allowed Elisha to kiss his parents, Jesus does not. The implication is christologically sharp: the call of Christ is *greater* than the call of Elijah. The prophetic succession is a type; the discipleship of the Son is the antitype, and it brooks no qualifier. The chapter that ends with Elisha burning his plow ends, canonically, with every reader of the Gospels being asked whether their own plow is sufficiently burned.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Adderet* — the prophet's distinctive mantle, attested also in 2 Kings 2:8, 13-14, where Elisha receives it after Elijah's ascension. *Keli* (implements, v. 21) is a generic word for *equipment, utensils, instruments* — the plowing gear becomes firewood. *Sharat* — the priestly ministry verb; Elisha begins as Elijah's *attendant*, the same role Joshua had to Moses. The succession runs through service."
